    {
      "id": 75,
      "project": "Nexus",
      "summary": "v3.6.1: Fixed all 5 findings from the Overseer's first successful self-audit. Atomic _flush (write to .tmp then rename — crash-safe), write mutex on _flush (prevents concurrent truncation), semantic auto-link promise cap (max 3 in flight), embedding cache debounced to 5s with process.exit flush, usage burn rate sorts history by timestamp before calculating. Also shipped the infrastructure that made the self-audit possible: aiFetch (undici, no 5min headers timeout), AI semaphore (one inference at a time), GPU-aware signal (tuned thresholds for CPU-bound generation). The Overseer read 15 files / 46k tokens of its own source code in 15.7 minutes on the local RTX 3070 Ti and found real bugs we missed.",
      "decisions": [
        "Atomic _flush via write-to-tmp-then-rename pattern — renameSync is atomic on same filesystem, crash between steps leaves either .tmp or .bak as valid recovery point",
        "Write mutex is a simple boolean flag, not a true async lock — sufficient because Node is single-threaded and _flush is synchronous",
        "Semantic auto-link capped at 3 concurrent fire-and-forget promises — prevents accumulation without blocking recordDecision",
        "Embedding cache debounced to 5s via setTimeout with process.exit handler — balances I/O cost vs data freshness",
        "Self-audit infrastructure: aiFetch (undici no timeout) + AI semaphore + GPU signal = three-layer protection that let the Overseer read its own codebase for the first time"
      ],
      "blockers": [],
      "files_touched": [
        "server/db/store.ts",
        "server/lib/embeddings.ts",
        "server/routes/estimator.ts"
      ],
      "tags": [
        "v3.6.1",
        "self-audit-fixes",
        "atomic-flush",
        "mutex",
        "embeddings",
        "burn-rate"
      ],
      "created_at": "2026-04-10T07:33:46.936Z"
    },
    {
      "id": 76,
      "project": "nexus",
