      "recommendation": "## PLAN\nFocus on stabilizing the core combat mechanics by implementing hex effect triggers and tuning movement weights to ensure gameplay loop integrity.\n\n## TASKS\n1. [30m] Hex system: wire active_hexes on units — Ensures ForceRegistry effects (void, lethargy, etc.) actually apply to entities, fixing a broken combat loop.\n2. [45m] Force weight tuning — Playtest and adjust field/hex/flee weights — Critical for the \"feel\" of movement; prevents players from being stuck or moving erratically.\n3. [15m] Index Noosphere decisions into The Ledger — Maintains project continuity and ensures technical architecture decisions are documented before session end.\n\n## RATIONALE\nThe total estimated time is 90 minutes, fitting within the 108-minute runway with a small buffer for context switching. I prioritized the Hex system because it is a functional dependency for all subsequent combat audits (Moxie/Ego Hunter), followed by tuning to ensure the foundation is solid before moving to higher-level systems.\n\n## AVOID\n- Noosphere Phase 1: PULSE — Too high-risk and computationally heavy for the current session window; requires dedicated deep-work blocks.\n- AUDIT: MYE/Ego Hunter coverage — Defer until the Hex system wiring is verified, as these audits depend on functional hex effects.",
